{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16239"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16239"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74621"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8930"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8397"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74621"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological appearance of cells can provide important diagnostic information in breast pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical histological appearance of Paget cells in the nipple epidermis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small cells with hyperchromatic nuclei","Small cells with dense eosinophilic cytoplasm","Multinucleated giant cells with granular cytoplasm","Large cells with clear cytoplasm and round nuclei","Spindle-shaped cells with elongated nuclei"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPaget cells are characteristically \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge cells with clear cytoplasm and round nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E. They are found within the epidermis of the nipple in Paget disease of the breast. The clear appearance is due to the presence of mucopolysaccharides in their cytoplasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cells with hyperchromatic nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E - This better describes typical malignant cells but not the specific appearance of Paget cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpindle-shaped cells with elongated nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes mesenchymal cells rather than the epithelial Paget cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultinucleated giant cells with granular cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more characteristic of inflammatory cells rather than Paget cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cells with dense eosinophilic cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes normal keratinocytes rather than the pale-staining Paget cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaget cells are actually adenocarcinoma cells that have migrated from an underlying ductal carcinoma to colonise the nipple epidermis. Their distinctive appearance helps differentiate them from normal epidermal cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paget cells are large, pale-staining cells with clear cytoplasm found in the epidermis of the nipple in Paget disease of the breast.","Paget cells contain mucopolysaccharides which give them their characteristic clear appearance on histological examination."],"references":["Smith AA. Pre-Paget cells: Evidence of keratinocyte origin of extramammary Paget\u0027s disease. Intractable Rare Dis Res. 2019 Aug;8(3):203-205. doi: 10.5582/irdr.2019.01096. PMID: 31523599; PMCID: PMC6743430.","Markarian S, Holmes DR. Mammary Paget\u0027s Disease: An Update. Cancers (Basel). 2022 May 13;14(10):2422. doi: 10.3390/cancers14102422. PMID: 35626023; PMCID: PMC9139704.","Karakas C. Paget\u0027s disease of the breast. J Carcinog. 2011;10:31. doi: 10.4103/1477-3163.90676. Epub 2011 Dec 8. PMID: 22279416; PMCID: PMC3263015.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16239"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:24:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:57:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8930"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74621"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t